’s collective imagination and affirmed viewers in their multiple identities as local residents, national citizens, and transnational consumers. In a close reading of Toronto-based CBC dramas from the 1960s to 2010, VanderBurgh explains how the city has functioned as a strategic location in CBC programming, reflecting dramatically changing ideas about Canadian identity, community, and citizenship.At a time when many are suggesting that the era of television is over, What Television Remembers sounds the alarm that we are in danger of forgetting TV in Canada without appreciating the complexities of its contributions and legacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective memory and televisionzCanada. 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspectszOntariozToronto. 0aTelevision broadcastingzCanada. 0aTelevision broadcastingzOntariozToronto. 0aTelevision programszCanada. 0aTelevision programszOntariozToronto. 0aTelevisionxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aTelevisionxSocial aspectszOntariozToronto. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aCBC.  aCanadian TV history.  aCityTV.  aarchives.  abroadcast.  acommunications.  acultural.  afilm.  amedia studies.  amemory.  anationalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228019855?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228019855423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228019855/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packag